{
  "texts": [
    "Ültanir, 2012; Bodrova, 2003; Demirbaga, 2018; Grazzini, 2004; Grant-Miller, 2007; O'Donnell, 2013), it is an applied \"formal\" educational setting, essentially organised around an indirect form of teaching, in which pupils develop and learn dynamically by repeatedly interacting with their learning spaces and materials.",
    "Compared to today mainstream educational science that \"has only recently started to pay due attention to the significance of the material and spatial dimensions of learning\" (Nohl & Götz-Dehnavi, 2022; Pp. 325; also: Shapiro & Stolz, 2019), the MM has a long-standing tradition of so doing, and has been deployed in a wide variety of cultural and social contexts (e.g., Murray et al., 2023.",
    "See also: Whitescarver & Cossentino, 2007).",
    "In terms of schools, the most traditional and well-known approach (at least in western societies) is surely the \"teacher-centred\" approach in which teachers supply the knowledge that pupils must acquire, and then evaluate the efficiency of the training through tests, grades, etc (e.g., Serin, 2018; see also: Scheurs, J., & Dumbraveanu, 2014; Muthukrishna, 2023; White & Muthukrishna, 2023).",
    "Despite being necessarily multimodal -e.g., books combine images and written text; music classes, sounds and written notes, passing a test has social and emotional components -these \"traditional teacher-centered\" methods bear similarities to the training of disembodied entities such as LLMs."
  ]
}